'''Human-information interaction''' or '''HII''' is the formal term for [[Information seeking behavior|information behavior research]] in [[archival science]]; the term was invented by Nahum Gershon in 1995.<ref>{{cite book |last=Morville |first=Peter |date=26 September 2009 |title=Ambient Findability: What We Find Changes Who We Become |url=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=xJNLJXXbhusC |location=Sebastopol, CA |publisher=[[O'Reilly Media]] |page=53 |isbn= 9780596553012 |author-link= }}</ref> HII is not transferrable from analog to digital research because nonprofessional researchers greatly emphasize the need for further elaboration of context and scope finding aid elements. Researchers in HII take on many tasks, including helping to design [[information systems]] from a biological perspective that conform to the requirements of different segments of society, along with other behaviour intended to improve interaction between humans and information systems. HII is generally considered to be [[multi-disciplinary]] as different disciplines have different viewpoints on these interactions and their consequences.<ref>{{cite book |last=Fidel |first=Raya |date=23 March 2012|title=Human Information Interaction: An Ecological Approach to Information Behavior|url=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=-erlCTVFDUQC |location=Cambridge, MA |publisher=[[MIT Press]] |page=x-xix |isbn=9780262300704 |author-link= }}</ref> HII is considered especially important due to humanity's dependence on information and the technology needed to access it.<ref>{{cite book |last=Pirolli |first=Peter |date=2002 |title= Encyclopedia of Life Support Systems |chapter= Vol. I: Human-information interaction: technology and theory |url=http://www.eolss.net/sample-Chapters/C01/E6-72-02-02.pdf |location=Oxford, UK |publisher=[[UNESCO]] |page= |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref>
